Since $AC$ is a diameter, $\angle ABC$ and $\angle ADC$ are right angles.  Also, $\angle ADB = \angle ACB = 180^\circ - 45^\circ - 90^\circ = 45^\circ$.

[asy]
unitsize(1 cm);

pair A, B, C, D;

A = (0,0);
C = (2,0);
B = intersectionpoint(arc(A,sqrt(2),0,180),arc(C,sqrt(2),0,180));
D = intersectionpoint(arc(A,sqrt(2),0,180),arc(C,sqrt(2),90,270));

draw(Circle(A,sqrt(2)));
draw(A--B--C--D--cycle);
draw(A--C);

label("$A$", A, SW);
label("$B$", B, NE);
label("$C$", C, SE);
label("$D$", D, NW);
label("$30^\circ$", (0.3,0.1));
label("$45^\circ$", (0.7,0.2));
label("$45^\circ$", (1.3,0.2));
label("$90^\circ$", (1,0.4));
label("$90^\circ$", (1,-0.4));
[/asy]

Since $\triangle ABD$ is a 45-45-90 triangle, $AD = BD = \sqrt{2} AB$.  Since $\triangle ABC$ is a 45-45-90 triangle, $AB = BC = AC/\sqrt{2} = \sqrt{2} AD$.  Therefore, $AD = BD = AB/2$.

The area of $\triangle ABD$ is $\frac{1}{2} \cdot AD \cdot BD = \frac{1}{2} \cdot \frac{AB}{2} \cdot \frac{AB}{2} = \frac{AB^2}{8}$.

The area of $\triangle ABC$ is $\frac{1}{2} \cdot AB \cdot BC = \frac{1}{2} \cdot AB \cdot AB = \frac{AB^2}{2}$.

The area of quadrilateral $ABCD$ is then $\frac{AB^2}{8} + \frac{AB^2}{2} = \frac{5}{8} AB^2$.

The area of the circle is $\pi (AC/2)^2 = \pi (AB)^2/2$.

The ratio of the area of quadrilateral $ABCD$ to the area of the circle is $\frac{5}{8} AB^2 / \left(\pi (AB)^2/2\right) = \frac{5}{4\pi}$.  Therefore, $a + b + c = 5 + 16 + 4 = \boxed{25}$.

